" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ccat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Corporate/Industrial News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c22"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gtrans"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c22"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c22"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpin"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Industry News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:c22"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Transport app Citymapper offers alternatives when MRT breaks down</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SINGAPORE - At a loss when trains break down? Transport app provider Citymapper has introduced a feature in its wayfinding platform which will not only alert commuters to a rail glitch as soon as it happens, but suggests alternative routes as well.</Para><Para>For instance, if there is a breakdown on the Downtown Line between Beauty World and Bugis stations, the free app will suggest taking Bus Service 170.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Citymapper has rail alerts in cities such such as Hong Kong, London, Paris and New York City. In Hong Kong, it claims it is the only app which offers the alternative route option when incidents occur on the MTR.</Para><Para>In Singapore, it is believed to be the first to offer this option.</Para><Para>The app taps into information available on the Land Transport Authority's Datamall. The moment there is a disruption, the app will have five suggested alternative routes.</Para><Para>If a user has a favourite MRT line, he or she can also choose to be notified when a disruption occurs on that line.</Para><Para>Patsy Ho, Citymapper's city operations manager for Asia, said: "We can launch this feature when there is enough data provided, preferably from an official source that has first-hand information about the metro status.</Para><Para>Citymapper's website interface that helps suggest alternative routes for commuters when trains breakdown. PHOTO: SCREENSHOT FROM CITYMAPPER.COM</Para><Para>"The data also needs to be machine-readable so that robots can handle it in real-time. In Singapore, the hard work is in phrasing the alert messages so that we, and thus the users, can quickly understand which part of the MRT line is affected."</Para><Para>Commuters here often complain about not having adequate and timely information on what they should do after a rail breakdown, despite efforts by operators to offer stop-gap measures such as bus-bridging services and free regular buses.</Para><Para>Commenting on the app, Singapore University of Social Sciences senior lecturer and transport economist Walter Theseira said "the real value-add is in the re-routing advice", but said "some testing is required to determine if the advice the app gives on re-routing is actually superior to following the recovery plans of the rail operator". circleline-1603.jpg Related StorySMRT app aims to help commuters beat the crowds at stations Related StoryRare ridership dip on North-South, East-West MRT lines Related StoryMajor MRT faults remain at record high but overall distance-based reliability improves</Para><Para>"For example, we don't know if bus bridging services are faster, or if taking an alternative route is faster - as when people divert themselves to alternative routes, those routes get congested as well, which may impact travel times," Dr Theseira added. "I am not sure if the re-routing algorithm they have deployed takes such effects into account.</Para><Para>"Probably the greatest benefit will be to commuters who haven't yet entered the area of disruption, and who can still re-route effectively by avoiding the disruption zone entirely."</Para><Para>Commuter Jeff Chew said he found the Citymapper app somewhat "unwieldy" even if "it has a lot of features".</Para><Para>The 80-year-old retiree who uses public transport regularly said: "It's a good idea, and it is quite promising. But it is hard to know how useful it is unless there is a real breakdown."</Para><Para>He added that it is also not as "intuitive" as another travel app - gothere.sg - he uses. "But of course, that does not have breakdown contingency," he noted.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Christopher Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

